      "title": "Defining Scale of Temperature",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Defining Scale of Temperature</strong></h3><p>${{\\text{T}}_{\\text{C}}}=\\text{T}-273.15$ (1)</p><p>Equation (1) shows the relation between the temperatures in celsius scales and kelvin scale. Because the size of a degree is the same on the two scales, a temperature difference of $10\\text{C}$ is equal to a temperature difference of $10\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ K}$. The two scales differ only in the choice of the zero point. The ice point temperature on the kelvin scale, $273.15\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ K}$, corresponds to $0.00\\text{C}$ and the Kelvin steam point $373.15\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ K}$, is equivalent to $100.00\\text{C}$.</p><p>A common temperature scale in everyday use in US is the Fahrenheit scale. The ice point in this scale is $32\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ F}$ and the steam point is $212\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ F}$. These two are divided in 180 equal parts. The relation between Celsius scale and Fahrenheit scale is derived below.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"469\" height=\"132\"></p><p>100 parts of Celsius scale $=180$ parts of Fahrenheit scale</p><p>1 part of Celsius scale $=\\frac{9}{5}$ parts of Fahrenheit scale</p><p>Hence</p><p>${{\\text{T}}_{\\text{F}}}=32+\\frac{9}{5}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{T}}_{\\text{C}}}$ (2)</p><p>Further</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{T}}_{\\text{C}}}=\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ T}=\\frac{5}{9}\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{T}}_{\\text{F}}}$ (3)</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"365\" height=\"130\"></p><p>Relation among Kelvin, Celsius and Fahrenheit temperature scales</p>",
      "position": 0,
